// Cipherstash integration example schema.
//
// One model exercising every cipherstash codec id the extension
// ships — string, double, bigint, date, boolean, and json — with a
// representative search-config flag set per column. The no-args
// constructors default every `equality` / `orderAndRange` /
// `freeTextSearch` / `searchableJson` flag to `true`, opting each
// column into the maximal index surface its codec supports; the
// explicit-args sites below opt specific columns out to demonstrate
// the gating semantics.
//
// Operator visibility per column follows from the codec's trait
// set (per spec D7):
//
//   - `email` (string) — `cipherstashEq`, `cipherstashIlike`,
//     `cipherstashNotIlike` (free-text-search), plus
//     `cipherstashGt` / `Gte` / `Lt` / `Lte` / `Between` / `NotBetween`
//     / `InArray` / `NotInArray` (order-and-range + equality).
//   - `salary` (double) — equality + order-and-range.
//   - `accountId` (bigint) — equality + order-and-range.
//   - `birthday` (date) — equality + order-and-range.
//   - `emailVerified` (boolean) — equality only.
//   - `preferences` (json) — `cipherstashJsonbPathExists` plus the
//     SELECT-expression helpers `cipherstashJsonbPathQueryFirst` /
//     `cipherstashJsonbGet`.

model User {
  id            String @id
  email         cipherstash.EncryptedString()
  salary        cipherstash.EncryptedDouble()
  accountId     cipherstash.EncryptedBigInt()     @map("accountid")
  birthday      cipherstash.EncryptedDate()
  emailVerified cipherstash.EncryptedBoolean()    @map("emailverified")
  preferences   cipherstash.EncryptedJson()

  // The CipherStash EQL bundle (eql-2.2.1) hits a SQL-injection-style bug
  // in `eql_v2.add_encrypted_constraint` when the table or column name needs
  // quoting (reserved words, mixed case, etc.) — the constraint-name format
  // string interpolates `%I` for both the prefix and the (already
  // double-quoted) identifier, producing invalid SQL like
  // `CONSTRAINT eql_v2_encrypted_constraint_"users"_"accountId"`.
  //
  // `user` is reserved in Postgres, so we map the table to `users`; the
  // mixed-case columns (`accountId`, `emailVerified`) are mapped to
  // lowercase column names so `%I` renders them unquoted. Filed upstream —
  // drop these `@map` / `@@map` overrides once the bundle is fixed and we
  // re-vendor.
  @@map("users")
}
